                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-406-off2281 t18260914-406-victim2102"></join>
                     </persName>
                  , from his person
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>JOHN SPRIGGS MORSS CHURCHILL. I am a <rs id="t18260914-406-viclabel2283" type="occupation">bookseller</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-406-victim2102 t18260914-406-viclabel2283"></join>, and live in Leicester-square. On the night of the 8th of<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182609140155"></xptr>July I was in <placeName id="t18260914-406-crimeloc2284">Bedford-street, Covent-garden</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-406-crimeloc2284" type="placeName" value="Bedford-street, Covent-garden"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-406-crimeloc2284" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-406-off2281 t18260914-406-crimeloc2284"></join>, and felt a hand at my pocket - I turned round, and saw the prisoner take my handkerchief from his coat, and throw it away; he ran off - I pursued him to the corner of Bedford-court, and took him in Henrietta-street; I never got my handkerchief again; I think it was my handkerchief I saw in his hands, but I am not certain - it was a red one, and so was mine; when I came up to him, I said, "You have robbed me!" I was taking him to the watch-house, when the beadle came up and took him; I saw him take it out of his bosom, and throw it on the pavement; there was some person said, "Let him go;" I said he was not the first person I had prosecuted.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-406-person2103">
                  JAMES 
                  BETHELL
               <interp inst="t18260914-406-person2103" type="surname" value="BETHELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-406-person2103" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-406-person2103" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the beadle. I was in the street at half-past nine o'clock, and heard the cry of Stop thief! I took the prisoner to the watch-house, and found nothing on him; the prosecutor charged him with this robbery, and he did not deny it.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was walking with a friend, and got joking him - when we got to Probert's hotel, he was offended; I ran down Bedford-street, this gentleman was coming after me, and I thought it was him, as he had said he would put me into the watch-house.</p>
               <p>Mr. CHURCHILL. He said at Bow-street, that there was a row, and he ran, and I followed him, crying Stop thief! he said he heard the rattles sprung, but the watchmen do not come till ten o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18260914-406-verdict2285" type="verdictDescription">
